Infrastructure Overview:

- 1 Domain Name: foobar.com
- DNS Record: www -> 8.8.8.8
- 1 Server:
  - Nginx (Web Server)
  - Application Server
  - Application Files (Codebase)
  - MySQL Database

Request Flow:

- User enters www.foobar.com in the browser.
- DNS resolves www.foobar.com to 8.8.8.8 using an A record.
- Request is sent to the server.
- Nginx receives the HTTP/HTTPS request.
- Static files are served directly by Nginx.
- Dynamic requests are forwarded to the Application Server.
- The Application Server processes the request.
- If needed, it queries MySQL Database.
- MySQL returns data to the Application Server.
- Response is sent back through Nginx to the user.

Components:

Server:
- A server is a machine that provides services over a network.

Domain Name:
- Provides a human-readable address instead of an IP.
- Example: www.foobar.com

DNS Record:
- Type: A Record
- Maps domain name to IPv4 address.

Web Server:
- Software: Nginx
- Handles HTTP/HTTPS requests.
- Serves static content.
- Forwards dynamic requests.

Application Server:
- Runs application logic.
- Processes business rules.
- Connects with database.

Database:
- Software: MySQL
- Stores persistent data.
- Retrieves and updates information.

Communication:
- Protocols: HTTP / HTTPS
- Ports: 80 / 443

Issues:

- SPOF:
  - Only one server exists.
  - If it fails, the whole website is unavailable.

- Downtime:
  - Restarting services during updates causes downtime.

- Scalability:
  - A single server has limited resources.
  - Cannot handle large traffic efficiently.
